Energy from the Sun

The Sun transfers energy to Earth via electromagnetic radiation (mostly visible light and infrared). Most of our energy resources are indirect results of the Sun's energy.

  • The Sun heats the atmosphere, creating wind and producing waves.
  • Water evaporated by the Sun falls as rain, filling up reservoirs for hydroelectric power.
  • Plants grown via sunlight form the basis for fuels like biofuels and fossil fuels.

Some resources do not come from the Sun: Geothermal (Earth's core), Nuclear (elements), and Tidal (Moon's gravity).

Solar Cells & Panels

Solar cells (photovoltaic cells) convert light energy directly into electrical energy. Solar panels are used for heating water; they absorb thermal energy from the Sun to heat water flowing through pipes within the panel.

(Please refer to the diagrams of a solar cell and a solar panel).

Energy from Fuels

Fuels are substances that can be reacted with other substances to release energy, usually in the form of heat. This energy is a type of chemical energy.

Fossil Fuels

Formed from the remains of dead organisms over millions of years. Examples include coal, oil, and natural gas. Burning them (combustion) releases thermal energy.

Biofuels

Derived from organic matter, like plants or animal waste. They are renewable. Examples include biogas and ethanol.

Nuclear Fuel

Uranium is the main fuel for nuclear power. Energy is released through nuclear fission, where uranium nuclei are split. This process does not involve burning and produces no greenhouse gases, but it does create hazardous radioactive waste.

Energy from Water

Water can be used to generate electricity in several ways, primarily by turning turbines.

Hydroelectric Power

Rainwater is collected in a reservoir behind a dam. This water has gravitational potential energy. When released, it flows through pipes, turning turbines to generate electricity.

Wave Power

Waves on the sea surface cause a floating generator to move up and down, which drives a piston to turn a turbine.

Tidal Power

A barrage is built across a river estuary. As the tide comes in, water flows through turbines. When the tide goes out, it flows back through the turbines, generating electricity in both directions.

(Please refer to the diagrams for each type of water power generation).

Geothermal Energy

Geothermal energy comes from the thermal energy stored within the Earth. This heat originates from the radioactive decay of elements deep in the Earth's core.

  • In volcanic regions, rocks are hot enough to boil water.
  • Cold water is pumped down to the hot rocks.
  • The water boils and returns to the surface as steam under high pressure.
  • This steam is used to turn turbines which generate electricity.

Nuclear Fusion

The Sun releases energy through nuclear fusion in its core. This process involves fusing small nuclei (like hydrogen) together to form larger nuclei (like helium), releasing massive amounts of energy.

Scientists are researching how to create fusion reactors on Earth. This requires extremely high temperatures and pressures, similar to a star's core.

If successful, fusion could provide virtually limitless, carbon-free energy. Current research requires almost as much energy to run as is produced, but progress is being made toward net energy production.
